    <main>
        <section id="setting">
            <h2>Setting</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Hailsham:</strong> A boarding school representing innocence and ignorance. Example: *“We loved our sports pavilion...”* (p. 7).</li>
                <li><strong>The Pond:</strong> A place of reflection. Example: *“Once you came out to the pond, you’d find a tranquil atmosphere...”* (p. 25).</li>
                <li><strong>The Gallery:</strong> A mysterious collection of artwork. Example: *“What is this gallery? Why should she have a gallery of things done by us?”* (p. 31).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="characters">
            <h2>Characters</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Kathy H.:</strong> Empathetic, reflective, and resilient. Example: *“I’ve been getting this urge to order all these old memories.”* (p. 37).</li>
                <li><strong>Tommy:</strong> Sensitive and impulsive. Example: *“She said I shouldn’t worry. Not mind what other people were saying.”* (p. 27).</li>
                <li><strong>Ruth:</strong> Ambitious and manipulative, but vulnerable. Example: *“She’s scared of us.”* (p. 33).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="themes">
            <h2>Themes</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Memory and Identity:</strong> Explores how memories shape identity. Example: *“I’ve been getting this urge to order all these old memories.”* (p. 37).</li>
                <li><strong>Ethics of Science:</strong> Questions the morality of cloning and organ donation. Example: *“What is this gallery?”* (p. 31).</li>
                <li><strong>Mortality and Purpose:</strong> Addresses the inevitability of death. Example: *“We weren’t being taught enough about what’s going to happen to us one day.”* (p. 29).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="important-moments">
            <h2>Important Moments</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Tommy’s tantrums: Reflects his frustration and rejection. Example: *“Tommy burst into thunderous bellowing...”* (p. 10).</li>
                <li>Madame’s fear: Highlights the clones’ dehumanization. Example: *“Madame froze and waited for us to pass by...”* (p. 35).</li>
                <li>Miss Lucy’s frustration: Reveals hints about their future. Example: *“We weren’t being taught enough about what’s going to happen to us one day.”* (p. 29).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="questions">
            <h2>Questions</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Why is creativity so highly valued at Hailsham?</li>
                <li>What is the purpose of the Gallery?</li>
                <li>How does Kathy’s reflective tone shape our understanding of her identity?</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="additional-sections">
            <h2>Additional Sections</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Symbols:</strong> The Tape - Represents nostalgia. Example: *“I kept listening to it over and over...”* (p. 45).</li>
                <li><strong>Literary Devices:</strong> Imagery - *“The pavilion reminded us of those sweet little cottages...”* (p. 7).</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
